President Joseph R. Biden has declared a state of emergency in California due to the Caldor Fire, which started on August 14, 2021. This declaration authorizes the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts to help the local population affected by the fire. FEMA is authorized to provide equipment and resources to alleviate the impacts of the emergency, with emergency protective measures funded at 75 percent by the federal government. Dolph A. Diemont has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.